WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.454 --> 00:00:03.537
(enlightening music)

2
00:00:07.980 --> 00:00:11.430
<v ->We're gonna do the last of the emergency medicine topics:</v>

3
00:00:11.430 --> 00:00:13.630
infectious disease, allergy, and toxicology.

4
00:00:16.140 --> 00:00:16.973
Here we go.

5
00:00:16.973 --> 00:00:18.240
I'm gonna try to cover soft tissue infection,

6
00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:19.890
animal bites, tick-related illnesses,

7
00:00:19.890 --> 00:00:22.740
acute allergic reactions, toxicology in the half hour.

8
00:00:22.740 --> 00:00:26.580
We can do it. Your stomach will make it, honest.

9
00:00:26.580 --> 00:00:28.650
All right, so I just wanna talk

10
00:00:28.650 --> 00:00:31.080
about infectious disease topic,

11
00:00:31.080 --> 00:00:33.450
in particular topic of cellulitis.

12
00:00:33.450 --> 00:00:37.170
And here I want you to recognize

13
00:00:37.170 --> 00:00:41.100
that the Infectious Disease Society of America says

14
00:00:41.100 --> 00:00:44.790
when you have a patient who has cellulitis, okay,

15
00:00:44.790 --> 00:00:46.140
the residents do it all the time,

16
00:00:46.140 --> 00:00:49.140
I'm admitting a patient for cellulitis,

17
00:00:49.140 --> 00:00:53.610
I always have to say it's recommended you give the prefects.

18
00:00:53.610 --> 00:00:55.740
Is it a non-purulent cellulitis

19
00:00:55.740 --> 00:00:59.190
or is it a purulent cellulitis, right?

20
00:00:59.190 --> 00:01:00.570
Why?

21
00:01:00.570 --> 00:01:04.350
Because it will tell you almost immediately

22
00:01:04.350 --> 00:01:06.630
what the organisms you're dealing with.

23
00:01:06.630 --> 00:01:09.870
Non-purulent cellulitis, the picture on the left,

24
00:01:09.870 --> 00:01:12.330
we all have seen this patient, right,

25
00:01:12.330 --> 00:01:15.090
that's either strep pyogenes, group A beta-hemolytic strep,

26
00:01:15.090 --> 00:01:16.923
or it's MSSA, right?

27
00:01:16.923 --> 00:01:18.723
It's staph or strep, right?

28
00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:21.507
The one that's purulent,

29
00:01:21.507 --> 00:01:24.570
the one with the one puss is coming out of it

30
00:01:24.570 --> 00:01:27.360
or associated with it or big abcess is,

31
00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:28.950
soft tissue infection is typically

32
00:01:28.950 --> 00:01:31.083
community-acquired MRSA.

33
00:01:31.980 --> 00:01:35.070
Now I said the word MRSA

34
00:01:35.070 --> 00:01:37.770
and then I gave it the prefix community-acquired.

35
00:01:37.770 --> 00:01:40.500
So let me go back, give you a little history on MRSA

36
00:01:40.500 --> 00:01:43.562
'cause everybody's all, "It's MRSA."

37
00:01:43.562 --> 00:01:45.510
Let's just do this.

38
00:01:45.510 --> 00:01:48.900
When Fleming developed penicillin, okay,

39
00:01:48.900 --> 00:01:50.580
when he developed penicillin,

40
00:01:50.580 --> 00:01:55.440
penicillin initially could kill staph aureus.

41
00:01:55.440 --> 00:01:56.430
No problem.

42
00:01:56.430 --> 00:01:59.527
But within one year, staph aureus said,

43
00:01:59.527 --> 00:02:02.640
"I'm gonna make resistance to that," all right?

44
00:02:02.640 --> 00:02:06.660
So we suddenly had staph aureus resistance to penicillin.

45
00:02:06.660 --> 00:02:09.960
So what did we do? We made semisynthetic penicillins.

46
00:02:09.960 --> 00:02:11.640
We made methicillin.

47
00:02:11.640 --> 00:02:14.460
And so we had methicillin through the 1950s

48
00:02:14.460 --> 00:02:17.190
and into the early 1960s, right?

49
00:02:17.190 --> 00:02:18.023
Methicillin.

50
00:02:18.023 --> 00:02:21.997
And then in the early 1960s, staph aureus once again said,

51
00:02:21.997 --> 00:02:23.940
"I'm gonna make resistance that too."

52
00:02:23.940 --> 00:02:26.790
And that became the era of MRSA,

53
00:02:26.790 --> 00:02:29.880
methicillin-resistant staph aureus, in the early 1960s.

54
00:02:29.880 --> 00:02:32.130
Now it stayed at very, very, very low levels

55
00:02:32.130 --> 00:02:35.340
until the burgeoning of critical care

56
00:02:35.340 --> 00:02:36.677
and ICU medicine in all your hospitals

57
00:02:36.677 --> 00:02:39.030
in the late '70s, early '80s

58
00:02:39.030 --> 00:02:43.650
and all of a sudden, boom, MRSA took off in hospitals, okay,

59
00:02:43.650 --> 00:02:45.630
with our critically ill patients.

60
00:02:45.630 --> 00:02:49.500
And to this day, still kills approximately 16,000 patients

61
00:02:49.500 --> 00:02:51.030
per year in the United States

62
00:02:51.030 --> 00:02:55.890
from MRSA in the hospital, okay?

63
00:02:55.890 --> 00:02:57.840
All right, and as you know,

64
00:02:57.840 --> 00:03:00.360
that is a bug that's very, very difficult to kill.

65
00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:02.250
I mean, it's got resistance to like everything

66
00:03:02.250 --> 00:03:04.560
and then you have to put them on vanco, right?

67
00:03:04.560 --> 00:03:06.870
Vancomycin you need usually, typically.

68
00:03:06.870 --> 00:03:11.040
Well, in the mid '90s, late '90s, early 2000s,

69
00:03:11.040 --> 00:03:12.690
typically in ER, we start to see these patients

70
00:03:12.690 --> 00:03:15.150
coming in with abscesses on them, okay?

71
00:03:15.150 --> 00:03:17.850
And we ID them, culture 'em,

72
00:03:17.850 --> 00:03:21.750
and we got, "MRSA, what's that all about?

73
00:03:21.750 --> 00:03:24.840
MRSA," and then some deep dive.

74
00:03:24.840 --> 00:03:28.530
You looked at the genotype and phenotypes of the MRSA

75
00:03:28.530 --> 00:03:30.390
that's causing now these abscesses

76
00:03:30.390 --> 00:03:32.250
and it was completely different

77
00:03:32.250 --> 00:03:34.800
than what was sitting in the ICUs.

78
00:03:34.800 --> 00:03:38.100
It's genotype and phenotype was USSA 300 or 400,

79
00:03:38.100 --> 00:03:39.570
whereas the hospital-acquired ones

80
00:03:39.570 --> 00:03:41.850
where USA 100 or 500 typically.

81
00:03:41.850 --> 00:03:45.150
And what would happen with the USA 300s, 400,

82
00:03:45.150 --> 00:03:48.000
they had this predilection, they had this exotoxin

83
00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:50.790
called the Panton-Valentine leukocidin exotoxin

84
00:03:50.790 --> 00:03:52.830
that would create abscesses,

85
00:03:52.830 --> 00:03:56.160
which the original MRSA did not, okay?

86
00:03:56.160 --> 00:03:59.040
And what you will find is how these present,

87
00:03:59.040 --> 00:04:01.110
is they will present with all these abscesses

88
00:04:01.110 --> 00:04:02.497
and the patients invariably come in saying,

89
00:04:02.497 --> 00:04:04.560
"I think I got a spider bite."

90
00:04:04.560 --> 00:04:05.640
You've seen this patient, right?

91
00:04:05.640 --> 00:04:07.920
They get this tiny little eschar here in the middle,

92
00:04:07.920 --> 00:04:10.860
and they get this big abscess, and cellulitis surround it,

93
00:04:10.860 --> 00:04:12.420
and they get another one up here,

94
00:04:12.420 --> 00:04:15.600
and that's community-acquired MRSA.

95
00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:18.930
We first started seeing this first typically in patients

96
00:04:18.930 --> 00:04:21.690
who were in close proximity to each other.

97
00:04:21.690 --> 00:04:25.050
The first couple of reports on community-acquired MRSA

98
00:04:25.050 --> 00:04:28.020
was in a prison system in LA,

99
00:04:28.020 --> 00:04:30.720
then there was a wrestling team in Vermont that got it,

100
00:04:30.720 --> 00:04:33.150
eventually the then St. Louis Rams,

101
00:04:33.150 --> 00:04:34.400
all the linemen who were,

102
00:04:35.340 --> 00:04:36.510
you know, rubbing up against each other

103
00:04:36.510 --> 00:04:37.860
they got it all over them,

104
00:04:37.860 --> 00:04:40.260
and that was community-acquired MRSA.

105
00:04:40.260 --> 00:04:42.540
So you're encouraged now,

106
00:04:42.540 --> 00:04:47.540
when you have a patient who has a non-purulent or,

107
00:04:50.580 --> 00:04:54.480
cellulitis to say non-purulent 'cause it's strep or MSSA,

108
00:04:54.480 --> 00:04:57.964
and the treatment is there for the typical cellulitis,

109
00:04:57.964 --> 00:04:59.899
dicloxacillin, cephalexin, doxycycline,

110
00:04:59.899 --> 00:05:04.013
clindamycin, linezolid, versus community-acquired MRSA.

111
00:05:05.640 --> 00:05:07.830
From their abscesses after their I&amp;D,

112
00:05:07.830 --> 00:05:09.961
you can put them on trimethoprim-sulfa,

113
00:05:09.961 --> 00:05:11.860
doxycycline, clindamycin, and linezolid.

114
00:05:11.860 --> 00:05:13.920
Okay, a lot of times,

115
00:05:13.920 --> 00:05:18.030
and this happens I'm sure in all your hospitals,

116
00:05:18.030 --> 00:05:20.430
they will not do the genotype/phenotype testing for it.

117
00:05:20.430 --> 00:05:24.960
All you'll get on your report is MRSA, all right,

118
00:05:24.960 --> 00:05:25.890
when you culture it.

119
00:05:25.890 --> 00:05:26.887
And you may sit there saying,

120
00:05:26.887 --> 00:05:27.990
"Well, is that the hospital one

121
00:05:27.990 --> 00:05:30.180
or is it the community-acquired one?"

122
00:05:30.180 --> 00:05:31.680
Well, usually from history you can tell.

123
00:05:31.680 --> 00:05:33.750
But if you didn't even see the patient,

124
00:05:33.750 --> 00:05:37.470
you just look down at the sensitivities, all right?

125
00:05:37.470 --> 00:05:40.500
So in the community-acquired MRSA,

126
00:05:40.500 --> 00:05:41.430
the one with the abscesses,

127
00:05:41.430 --> 00:05:44.378
like you say, sensitive to trimethoprim-sulfa,

128
00:05:44.378 --> 00:05:45.563
sensitive to doxy, sensitive to clinda,

129
00:05:46.898 --> 00:05:48.780
they got a lot of Ss there.

130
00:05:48.780 --> 00:05:50.280
The hospital-acquired one,

131
00:05:50.280 --> 00:05:51.510
you look down at the sensitivities

132
00:05:51.510 --> 00:05:54.960
and all you see is R, R, R, resistant,

133
00:05:54.960 --> 00:05:56.187
until you get down to vanco.

134
00:05:56.187 --> 00:05:58.340
And that's how you know difference, okay,

135
00:05:58.340 --> 00:06:00.810
of the two types of MRSA.

136
00:06:00.810 --> 00:06:03.090
All right, now we're gonna go on

137
00:06:03.090 --> 00:06:05.400
to some other soft tissue infections.

138
00:06:05.400 --> 00:06:06.330
Now we got through that.

139
00:06:06.330 --> 00:06:07.950
How about the following question?

140
00:06:07.950 --> 00:06:08.783
Which of the following bites

141
00:06:08.783 --> 00:06:10.410
has the highest risk of infection?

142
00:06:10.410 --> 00:06:12.420
Cat bite to the hand, human bite to the face,

143
00:06:12.420 --> 00:06:14.610
dog bite to the thigh, or spider bite to the arm.

144
00:06:14.610 --> 00:06:16.833
Which one has the highest risk of infection?

145
00:06:22.110 --> 00:06:25.230
Yeah, so actually it's cat bite of the hand

146
00:06:25.230 --> 00:06:29.070
is the one that's the highest risk for a infection there.

147
00:06:29.070 --> 00:06:31.720
Okay, why cat bite of the hand?

148
00:06:31.720 --> 00:06:33.690
It's not that cats are worse than humans.

149
00:06:33.690 --> 00:06:34.920
Humans are worse than cats.

150
00:06:34.920 --> 00:06:36.020
Dogs are worse than...

151
00:06:37.770 --> 00:06:41.400
All animals have organisms in their mouth, right?

152
00:06:41.400 --> 00:06:45.870
Why the cat in this situation? Two reasons.

153
00:06:45.870 --> 00:06:47.670
It's the mechanism, all right?

154
00:06:47.670 --> 00:06:49.110
It's the mechanism, all right?

155
00:06:49.110 --> 00:06:52.170
So cats have some Pasteurella multocida in their mouth.

156
00:06:52.170 --> 00:06:54.920
Cats, they have these little sharp pointy teeth, right,

157
00:06:55.780 --> 00:06:57.000
and then they bite.

158
00:06:57.000 --> 00:06:59.640
And they're like perfect little autoinjectors,

159
00:06:59.640 --> 00:07:02.100
putting that Pasteurella right underneath your skin.

160
00:07:02.100 --> 00:07:04.980
You can't clean it out really well, right?

161
00:07:04.980 --> 00:07:06.810
And then the other part of that equation

162
00:07:06.810 --> 00:07:08.760
was it's on the hand.

163
00:07:08.760 --> 00:07:10.620
So I alluded to this the last lecture.

164
00:07:10.620 --> 00:07:15.000
Hand, feet are high risk places, all right?

165
00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:19.350
For those of you who picked human bite to the face, okay,

166
00:07:19.350 --> 00:07:22.290
so humans got organisms just like anybody else,

167
00:07:22.290 --> 00:07:26.160
but human bite to the face, the face rarely gets infected.

168
00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:28.110
You know, scalps rarely get infected.

169
00:07:28.110 --> 00:07:30.900
It's so well-vascularized, all right?

170
00:07:30.900 --> 00:07:32.460
So think about it for a moment,

171
00:07:32.460 --> 00:07:34.020
you know, talking about human bites.

172
00:07:34.020 --> 00:07:36.630
How many times you've bit your lip, right?

173
00:07:36.630 --> 00:07:39.450
Did it get infected? Of course not.

174
00:07:39.450 --> 00:07:41.550
You've got great vascular supply.

175
00:07:41.550 --> 00:07:44.190
So think about location and mechanism.

176
00:07:44.190 --> 00:07:47.160
In the case of cat bites, because of the high risk,

177
00:07:47.160 --> 00:07:49.530
you're gonna put them on amoxicillin-clavulanate.

178
00:07:49.530 --> 00:07:51.960
For human bites, and if you think it's at risk,

179
00:07:51.960 --> 00:07:54.330
of course then you can put them on amoxicillin-clavulanate

180
00:07:54.330 --> 00:07:55.500
and then make it really easy for yourself.

181
00:07:55.500 --> 00:07:58.920
For dog bites, it's also amoxicillin-clavulanate.

182
00:07:58.920 --> 00:08:01.320
You can close dog bites.

183
00:08:01.320 --> 00:08:02.520
People always ask that question.

184
00:08:02.520 --> 00:08:06.180
The answer is yes, providing you can do the following:

185
00:08:06.180 --> 00:08:07.980
that you can clean it out really well.

186
00:08:07.980 --> 00:08:10.770
And typically dog bites, unlike cat bites,

187
00:08:10.770 --> 00:08:12.810
you can clean out really well.

188
00:08:12.810 --> 00:08:14.910
'Cause what do dogs do?

189
00:08:14.910 --> 00:08:17.850
Unlike cats, who just do this little autoinjection thing,

190
00:08:17.850 --> 00:08:21.150
dogs bite and tear, okay?

191
00:08:21.150 --> 00:08:22.470
That's what they do.

192
00:08:22.470 --> 00:08:23.880
So you usually have a big open wound

193
00:08:23.880 --> 00:08:25.890
that you can clean out really well.

194
00:08:25.890 --> 00:08:27.600
The exception to the rule in dog bites

195
00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:29.160
would be police dogs.

196
00:08:29.160 --> 00:08:32.670
Police dogs are taught to bite and hold,

197
00:08:32.670 --> 00:08:34.680
and they get crush injuries, okay?

198
00:08:34.680 --> 00:08:36.870
But they do not do the tear.

199
00:08:36.870 --> 00:08:40.263
So don't mess around with a police dog, all right?

200
00:08:41.160 --> 00:08:42.390
Don't run away from a police dog,

201
00:08:42.390 --> 00:08:45.540
they will catch you and they will hurt you, okay?

202
00:08:45.540 --> 00:08:47.790
All right, here's the long list of other infections.

203
00:08:47.790 --> 00:08:50.040
I've already ran for the first three.

204
00:08:50.040 --> 00:08:51.813
Anthrax is another possibility.

205
00:08:52.650 --> 00:08:54.900
When you're dealing with animal hides and carcasses,

206
00:08:54.900 --> 00:08:57.600
think of anthrax.

207
00:08:57.600 --> 00:08:59.250
How many people watch "Doc Martin?"

208
00:08:59.250 --> 00:09:00.083
Did anybody watch a show "Doc Martin?"

209
00:09:00.083 --> 00:09:03.750
"Doc Martin" had a case of anthrax. I love that show.

210
00:09:03.750 --> 00:09:05.220
So far it's going away.

211
00:09:05.220 --> 00:09:06.813
There's freshwater injuries,

212
00:09:08.130 --> 00:09:09.720
that you put people on trimethoprim-sulfa

213
00:09:09.720 --> 00:09:10.980
and fluoroquinolones.

214
00:09:10.980 --> 00:09:12.330
The one I want you to really remember

215
00:09:12.330 --> 00:09:13.650
is the salt water injury.

216
00:09:13.650 --> 00:09:15.330
This is a potential problematic problem.

217
00:09:15.330 --> 00:09:17.040
Salt water injuries has vibrio,

218
00:09:17.040 --> 00:09:18.780
and you need to really hop on those

219
00:09:18.780 --> 00:09:21.090
and treat those appropriately.

220
00:09:21.090 --> 00:09:23.370
There you have a third-generation cephalosporin

221
00:09:23.370 --> 00:09:25.410
or fluoroquinolone and then the other two.

222
00:09:25.410 --> 00:09:27.030
I'm gonna move on. Cat scratch.

223
00:09:27.030 --> 00:09:28.470
Speaking of cats, one last thing,

224
00:09:28.470 --> 00:09:31.710
cat scratch is common enough.

225
00:09:31.710 --> 00:09:33.690
You see 22,000 cases a year.

226
00:09:33.690 --> 00:09:36.090
And they present, after the cat scratches,

227
00:09:36.090 --> 00:09:37.950
typically the upper extremity, right?

228
00:09:37.950 --> 00:09:40.410
Typically it's the upper extremity

229
00:09:40.410 --> 00:09:44.435
that you will then get this regional lymphadenopathy,

230
00:09:44.435 --> 00:09:47.283
epitrochlear lymph nodes, axillary lymph nodes.

231
00:09:48.330 --> 00:09:49.770
Many years ago, when I first trained,

232
00:09:49.770 --> 00:09:51.660
we didn't know what the organism is.

233
00:09:51.660 --> 00:09:53.700
The organism now is this gram-negative rod

234
00:09:53.700 --> 00:09:55.200
called Bartonella.

235
00:09:55.200 --> 00:09:57.450
That's the organism.

236
00:09:57.450 --> 00:10:00.390
It's a self-limiting disease, which is the good news.

237
00:10:00.390 --> 00:10:03.120
Your body eventually takes care of it in your lymph nodes

238
00:10:03.120 --> 00:10:05.760
so you don't have to do anything about it,

239
00:10:05.760 --> 00:10:07.680
but they will have this regional lymphadenopathy

240
00:10:07.680 --> 00:10:09.420
for one to two months.

241
00:10:09.420 --> 00:10:11.100
Don't do an I&amp;D.

242
00:10:11.100 --> 00:10:13.513
Now, when you go to UpToDate,

243
00:10:13.513 --> 00:10:15.510
because some of you're smart enough to go to UpToDate,

244
00:10:15.510 --> 00:10:17.640
they will say, "Oh, you know,

245
00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:19.320
if you have immunocompromised patients,

246
00:10:19.320 --> 00:10:21.060
we're gonna treat you with some antibiotics."

247
00:10:21.060 --> 00:10:22.023
Azithromycin.

248
00:10:23.040 --> 00:10:25.140
How about immunocompetent patients?

249
00:10:25.140 --> 00:10:27.150
Me and you, for example, okay?

250
00:10:27.150 --> 00:10:29.610
Some people say no, textbooks say no,

251
00:10:29.610 --> 00:10:32.430
some say yes, including UpToDate,

252
00:10:32.430 --> 00:10:36.840
based on a study of a whopping 29 patients

253
00:10:36.840 --> 00:10:40.770
who found that half of 'em, 14 or 15 of 'em,

254
00:10:40.770 --> 00:10:43.950
got azithromycin and had earlier resolution.

255
00:10:43.950 --> 00:10:46.740
So the authors of UpToDate, they like it.

256
00:10:46.740 --> 00:10:48.360
Because it's controversial,

257
00:10:48.360 --> 00:10:50.820
I can't imagine that question coming up on the boards,

258
00:10:50.820 --> 00:10:52.713
but I just want them to be complete.

259
00:10:54.540 --> 00:10:56.730
All right, question number two.

260
00:10:56.730 --> 00:10:58.110
A 24-year-old male presents

261
00:10:58.110 --> 00:10:59.910
with a three-day history of a rash

262
00:10:59.910 --> 00:11:02.040
that is increasing in size.

263
00:11:02.040 --> 00:11:04.320
It is not painful and it's not tender.

264
00:11:04.320 --> 00:11:05.153
It's just this rash

265
00:11:05.153 --> 00:11:06.390
that's getting bigger over the next three days.

266
00:11:06.390 --> 00:11:08.310
It's flat, it's oval, it's 14 centimeters

267
00:11:08.310 --> 00:11:09.480
by seven centimeters in size,

268
00:11:09.480 --> 00:11:10.740
I'll show you a picture in a second,

269
00:11:10.740 --> 00:11:12.600
has central clearing and has no fluctuance.

270
00:11:12.600 --> 00:11:15.270
No associated fevers or chills or systemic symptoms.

271
00:11:15.270 --> 00:11:17.820
No new medications, no recall of any insect bite.

272
00:11:17.820 --> 00:11:18.690
He recently vacationed

273
00:11:18.690 --> 00:11:20.610
on Martha's Vineyard in Massachusetts.

274
00:11:20.610 --> 00:11:21.443
This is a true case.

275
00:11:21.443 --> 00:11:23.580
I took this picture of this gentleman in my ER,

276
00:11:23.580 --> 00:11:24.720
and there you got it.

277
00:11:24.720 --> 00:11:28.890
And now based on that, in this case,

278
00:11:28.890 --> 00:11:31.950
you would A, prescribe ceftriaxone;

279
00:11:31.950 --> 00:11:34.440
B, prescribe doxycycline for 10 days;

280
00:11:34.440 --> 00:11:35.517
C, obtain a Lyme titer;

281
00:11:35.517 --> 00:11:37.920
and if positive, treat with ceftriaxone;

282
00:11:37.920 --> 00:11:39.350
D, obtain a Lyme titer;

283
00:11:39.350 --> 00:11:41.280
if positive, confirm with a Western blot study;

284
00:11:41.280 --> 00:11:43.773
and if positive, treat with ceftriaxone.

285
00:11:49.320 --> 00:11:51.570
B is the answer.

286
00:11:51.570 --> 00:11:54.960
So the rash there, you know,

287
00:11:54.960 --> 00:11:57.540
you all recognize where that rash is, right?

288
00:11:57.540 --> 00:11:59.610
Erythema migrans, all right?

289
00:11:59.610 --> 00:12:01.170
That's Lyme disease.

290
00:12:01.170 --> 00:12:04.500
And this is due to the spirochete, Borrelia burgdorferi,

291
00:12:04.500 --> 00:12:07.740
that lives in the gut of the deer tick.

292
00:12:07.740 --> 00:12:08.573
And what happens?

293
00:12:08.573 --> 00:12:12.510
The deer tick, typically the nymph stage,

294
00:12:12.510 --> 00:12:15.030
that's why you don't see them on you,

295
00:12:15.030 --> 00:12:17.490
typically the nymph stage gets on you,

296
00:12:17.490 --> 00:12:20.310
they are on there for about 36 hours to 48 hours,

297
00:12:20.310 --> 00:12:21.930
they have their blood meal.

298
00:12:21.930 --> 00:12:23.520
At the end of the blood meal,

299
00:12:23.520 --> 00:12:28.230
they regurgitate their stomach contents back into you

300
00:12:28.230 --> 00:12:30.210
and that's where the Borrelia burgdorferi

301
00:12:30.210 --> 00:12:33.450
has been hanging out, in the stomach contents of the tick.

302
00:12:33.450 --> 00:12:35.640
They regurgitate that into you

303
00:12:35.640 --> 00:12:38.280
and that's how you get the disease.

304
00:12:38.280 --> 00:12:39.423
Isn't that disgusting?

305
00:12:41.100 --> 00:12:43.388
Right before lunch too, right?

306
00:12:43.388 --> 00:12:44.880
Yeah, yeah, it's really disgusting.

307
00:12:44.880 --> 00:12:47.010
But that's how you get Lyme disease.

308
00:12:47.010 --> 00:12:50.070
All right, Lyme disease is all over the place.

309
00:12:50.070 --> 00:12:51.540
In my neck of the woods,

310
00:12:51.540 --> 00:12:54.900
this is almost daily visit in our ER,

311
00:12:54.900 --> 00:12:57.183
urgent care from someone with Lyme disease.

312
00:12:59.160 --> 00:13:02.040
As of when I last look,

313
00:13:02.040 --> 00:13:04.080
there's 48 states that's had Lyme disease.

314
00:13:04.080 --> 00:13:07.230
Oklahoma hasn't reported it, nor has Hawaii.

315
00:13:07.230 --> 00:13:08.940
If someone has some information about Oklahoma

316
00:13:08.940 --> 00:13:10.740
that I don't know about, pass it on to me.

317
00:13:10.740 --> 00:13:14.220
But as of yet, I'm unaware of Oklahoma

318
00:13:14.220 --> 00:13:16.140
having any Lyme disease.

319
00:13:16.140 --> 00:13:19.800
It might be there and just not recognized or reported.

320
00:13:19.800 --> 00:13:22.200
All right, so the early stages.

321
00:13:22.200 --> 00:13:23.730
Erythema migrans, I've already mentioned,

322
00:13:23.730 --> 00:13:25.680
happens in about two-thirds of the cases.

323
00:13:25.680 --> 00:13:28.380
They'll have the, quote, "bullseye" rash.

324
00:13:28.380 --> 00:13:30.720
I love it when they're perfect bullseye rashes

325
00:13:30.720 --> 00:13:33.090
like the pictures the CDC shows.

326
00:13:33.090 --> 00:13:36.360
They're big rashes. These things are large.

327
00:13:36.360 --> 00:13:39.390
They're not like just little dots all over the place, okay?

328
00:13:39.390 --> 00:13:42.060
They're good size areas of erythema.

329
00:13:42.060 --> 00:13:44.640
You may or may not have that central clearing.

330
00:13:44.640 --> 00:13:48.030
It doesn't hurt. People have mistaking it for cellulitis.

331
00:13:48.030 --> 00:13:49.890
But unlike cellulitis,

332
00:13:49.890 --> 00:13:53.730
it doesn't have the rubor, calor, dolor part, okay?

333
00:13:53.730 --> 00:13:54.720
It doesn't have that.

334
00:13:54.720 --> 00:13:56.587
You touch it, they're like, "Yeah, it doesn't bother me."

335
00:13:56.587 --> 00:13:58.170
"Yeah, it's not warm, it doesn't hurt,

336
00:13:58.170 --> 00:14:00.270
but it's a big red blotch," okay?

337
00:14:00.270 --> 00:14:02.470
It's not cellulitis, okay?

338
00:14:02.470 --> 00:14:06.540
All right, so the early diseases is the Lyme.

339
00:14:06.540 --> 00:14:09.600
Neurologic disease can show up early on.

340
00:14:09.600 --> 00:14:12.390
In my neck of the woods, when we see someone come in

341
00:14:12.390 --> 00:14:14.730
with a seventh nerve cranial palsy,

342
00:14:14.730 --> 00:14:16.830
we don't automatically say it's Bell's.

343
00:14:16.830 --> 00:14:18.570
Bell's is idiopathic.

344
00:14:18.570 --> 00:14:20.190
The patients in my neck of the woods,

345
00:14:20.190 --> 00:14:23.760
we consider Lyme disease as the cause.

346
00:14:23.760 --> 00:14:25.590
Cardiac disease, if you have a young, healthy person

347
00:14:25.590 --> 00:14:27.030
who suddenly has an AV block,

348
00:14:27.030 --> 00:14:29.280
you're like, "What's that all about,"

349
00:14:29.280 --> 00:14:30.633
think about Lyme disease.

350
00:14:31.890 --> 00:14:35.490
Later disease stages. There's the Lyme arthritis.

351
00:14:35.490 --> 00:14:39.750
It can be monoarticular or polyarticular.

352
00:14:39.750 --> 00:14:41.910
This is a case I had in the ER of a child.

353
00:14:41.910 --> 00:14:46.500
You can see both knees are huge and swollen and inflamed.

354
00:14:46.500 --> 00:14:49.380
I also took care of our VP at our hospital

355
00:14:49.380 --> 00:14:53.190
who had just one knee that's markedly swollen

356
00:14:53.190 --> 00:14:54.543
from Lyme disease.

357
00:14:55.530 --> 00:14:58.500
One of the points here, it's usually the large joints.

358
00:14:58.500 --> 00:15:02.040
It's almost always picked up on knees, hips is common,

359
00:15:02.040 --> 00:15:03.390
sometimes shoulders, elbows.

360
00:15:03.390 --> 00:15:06.210
It's not, "Oh, my fingers are hurting today,"

361
00:15:06.210 --> 00:15:08.190
you know, it's not one of those, right?

362
00:15:08.190 --> 00:15:10.590
Large joints get involved.

363
00:15:10.590 --> 00:15:12.570
Neurologic disease later can happen also

364
00:15:12.570 --> 00:15:15.300
in the post-Lyme syndrome,

365
00:15:15.300 --> 00:15:19.353
is also a possibility according to USDA.

366
00:15:20.400 --> 00:15:21.960
All right, so treatment.

367
00:15:21.960 --> 00:15:26.960
If you see the erythema migrans,

368
00:15:27.720 --> 00:15:30.957
you don't test, you just treat.

369
00:15:30.957 --> 00:15:32.610
You just treat, okay?

370
00:15:32.610 --> 00:15:35.610
If you decide to say, "I wanna do a Lyme titer anyway,"

371
00:15:35.610 --> 00:15:37.260
it's going to be negative.

372
00:15:37.260 --> 00:15:39.390
Most Lyme titers is your IgG.

373
00:15:39.390 --> 00:15:40.350
It takes four to six weeks

374
00:15:40.350 --> 00:15:42.873
for the IgG to turn positive, all right,

375
00:15:43.860 --> 00:15:47.160
while the rash is already present within about 10 to 14 days

376
00:15:47.160 --> 00:15:48.870
from the time of the tick bite.

377
00:15:48.870 --> 00:15:49.950
So it's going to be negative.

378
00:15:49.950 --> 00:15:52.650
So don't test, all right, just treat.

379
00:15:52.650 --> 00:15:55.200
And there's the treatment regimen up there.

380
00:15:55.200 --> 00:15:57.030
Children, I just put this in for completeness sake.

381
00:15:57.030 --> 00:15:59.493
I wouldn't memorize this, you'd look it up.

382
00:16:00.480 --> 00:16:03.420
So who do you test?

383
00:16:03.420 --> 00:16:05.790
All right, so you test patients

384
00:16:05.790 --> 00:16:07.590
in a two-tiered testing system

385
00:16:07.590 --> 00:16:10.680
if they have unexplained symptoms.

386
00:16:10.680 --> 00:16:12.750
So good case scenario:

387
00:16:12.750 --> 00:16:14.910
the patient who comes into my neck of the woods

388
00:16:14.910 --> 00:16:17.940
who's got a seventh nerve cranial palsy.

389
00:16:17.940 --> 00:16:19.170
They got, you know?

390
00:16:19.170 --> 00:16:22.650
Well, is it bells or is it Lyme? I don't know.

391
00:16:22.650 --> 00:16:26.880
So in that situation, I would do a Lyme titer.

392
00:16:26.880 --> 00:16:30.180
And if it's a positive or equivocal result,

393
00:16:30.180 --> 00:16:33.600
you then get the confirmatory Western blot.

394
00:16:33.600 --> 00:16:38.600
So it's a two-step testing for Lyme disease, okay?

395
00:16:38.700 --> 00:16:42.240
All right, and there is the rest of the treatment regimen.

396
00:16:42.240 --> 00:16:45.660
This is for completeness sake. Don't memorize.

397
00:16:45.660 --> 00:16:48.420
Is it 21 days, 28 days for this one, that one, that one?

398
00:16:48.420 --> 00:16:49.560
I can't believe they'd ask you that.

399
00:16:49.560 --> 00:16:51.810
That's just for completeness sake.

400
00:16:51.810 --> 00:16:55.830
When you do treat, just be aware that the patient,

401
00:16:55.830 --> 00:16:57.840
they have all these spirochetes in them, right?

402
00:16:57.840 --> 00:16:59.250
They have all these spirochetes in 'em.

403
00:16:59.250 --> 00:17:02.070
Just like syphilis, syphilis has spirochetes, right?

404
00:17:02.070 --> 00:17:03.510
So what happens when you give penicillin

405
00:17:03.510 --> 00:17:05.280
to a patient who has got syphilis?

406
00:17:05.280 --> 00:17:08.283
You can have the Jarisch-Herxheimer reaction, right?

407
00:17:09.900 --> 00:17:11.027
What happens?

408
00:17:11.027 --> 00:17:11.860
You give them the penicillin

409
00:17:11.860 --> 00:17:14.730
and what happens is those spirochetes start exploding

410
00:17:14.730 --> 00:17:17.940
and now it's got all this spirochete debris in you

411
00:17:17.940 --> 00:17:19.830
and you just feel crummy, okay?

412
00:17:19.830 --> 00:17:22.950
You get achy, low-grade fever, "I don't feel so good,

413
00:17:22.950 --> 00:17:26.790
my head aches," that lasts for a day and then it dissipates.

414
00:17:26.790 --> 00:17:30.000
Same thing when you're treating Lyme disease, okay?

415
00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:34.020
It's not an allergic reaction to the doxycycline, right?

416
00:17:34.020 --> 00:17:35.610
You just tell a patient, "That's good.

417
00:17:35.610 --> 00:17:37.440
It's good you're killing all those bad germs.

418
00:17:37.440 --> 00:17:40.980
Keep goin," and give 'em some Tylenol and he'll be fine.

419
00:17:40.980 --> 00:17:43.650
Okay, all right, Lyme disease prophylaxis.

420
00:17:43.650 --> 00:17:45.060
This is a question.

421
00:17:45.060 --> 00:17:48.090
Patient comes in, they've had a tick on them.

422
00:17:48.090 --> 00:17:51.720
You know, can you prophylax for Lyme disease?

423
00:17:51.720 --> 00:17:52.650
And the answer

424
00:17:52.650 --> 00:17:54.510
from the Infectious Disease Society of America

425
00:17:54.510 --> 00:17:57.990
is a single dose of doxycycline may be offered,

426
00:17:57.990 --> 00:18:00.870
a single dose meaning 200 milligrams, 2 tablets,

427
00:18:00.870 --> 00:18:04.080
can be offered as prophylaxis

428
00:18:04.080 --> 00:18:07.023
if the tick can be identified as a,

429
00:18:09.390 --> 00:18:12.960
I can't never say it, a deer tick, okay?

430
00:18:12.960 --> 00:18:15.420
All right, if it's a deer tick.

431
00:18:15.420 --> 00:18:16.560
Like, you can tell the difference

432
00:18:16.560 --> 00:18:19.590
between deer ticks and dog ticks and wood ticks, right?

433
00:18:19.590 --> 00:18:21.630
All right, it's been estimated to be on for 36 hours,

434
00:18:21.630 --> 00:18:24.030
and the prophylaxis can be started within 72 hours,

435
00:18:24.030 --> 00:18:26.970
and it happens in endemic area, like my area.

436
00:18:26.970 --> 00:18:27.803
And there's no contraindication,

437
00:18:27.803 --> 00:18:29.283
you give 'em the two tablets.

438
00:18:30.660 --> 00:18:32.820
All right, other dear tick-borne illnesses.

439
00:18:32.820 --> 00:18:36.720
Be aware, they can ask you questions about anaplasmosis.

440
00:18:36.720 --> 00:18:38.370
Anaplasmosis gives you this flu-like illness.

441
00:18:38.370 --> 00:18:39.870
So in our neck of the woods,

442
00:18:39.870 --> 00:18:41.820
so we see someone in the summertime

443
00:18:41.820 --> 00:18:43.953
coming in a flu-like illness.

444
00:18:45.240 --> 00:18:48.187
We'd say, "Mm, could it be anaplasmosis?"

445
00:18:48.187 --> 00:18:49.350
"They have fevers, chills, headaches.

446
00:18:49.350 --> 00:18:50.910
You do the blood work, they have thrombocytopenia,

447
00:18:50.910 --> 00:18:53.070
leukopenia and elevated LFTs," we say.

448
00:18:53.070 --> 00:18:54.630
That might be anaplasmosis.

449
00:18:54.630 --> 00:18:56.400
And then there's babesiosis,

450
00:18:56.400 --> 00:18:59.880
which also gives you more a malaria-like illness,

451
00:18:59.880 --> 00:19:02.160
high fevers, waxing and waning

452
00:19:02.160 --> 00:19:04.410
due to this intracellular protozoa

453
00:19:04.410 --> 00:19:06.870
and that kinda looks like malaria.

454
00:19:06.870 --> 00:19:08.130
So that babesiosis.

455
00:19:08.130 --> 00:19:09.420
The other tick-borne illness,

456
00:19:09.420 --> 00:19:10.920
just to be aware for the boards,

457
00:19:10.920 --> 00:19:12.150
is Rocky Mountain spotted fever.

458
00:19:12.150 --> 00:19:14.850
It has nothing to do with deer ticks.

459
00:19:14.850 --> 00:19:18.060
It's either a dog tick or a wood tick

460
00:19:18.060 --> 00:19:20.190
that will do this in endemic areas,

461
00:19:20.190 --> 00:19:23.040
typically more the southeastern United States

462
00:19:23.040 --> 00:19:27.810
where patients will come in flu-like illness again,

463
00:19:27.810 --> 00:19:30.120
but then they get the rash and multisystem involvement,

464
00:19:30.120 --> 00:19:33.510
you start thinking about Rocky Mountain spotted fever.

465
00:19:33.510 --> 00:19:35.460
Next one, changing topics.

466
00:19:35.460 --> 00:19:37.590
64-year-old male presents to the emergency department

467
00:19:37.590 --> 00:19:39.450
with diffuse pruritus and erythema

468
00:19:39.450 --> 00:19:41.640
along with facial and oral swelling.

469
00:19:41.640 --> 00:19:43.350
I'll show you a picture in a second.

470
00:19:43.350 --> 00:19:46.020
This occurs 15 minutes after eating peanuts.

471
00:19:46.020 --> 00:19:49.533
His blood pressure is 65 over 35, and his pulse is 120.

472
00:19:50.867 --> 00:19:51.700
This is what he looks like.

473
00:19:51.700 --> 00:19:53.490
His hands are swollen and red.

474
00:19:53.490 --> 00:19:56.520
He's got urticariac wheals all over his upper extremity

475
00:19:56.520 --> 00:19:57.570
and all over his body.

476
00:19:57.570 --> 00:20:00.270
His face is swollen, the lips are swollen.

477
00:20:00.270 --> 00:20:02.010
And he's hypotensive.

478
00:20:02.010 --> 00:20:03.930
This ain't good, right?

479
00:20:03.930 --> 00:20:07.110
Okay, so here's the case.

480
00:20:07.110 --> 00:20:09.120
And the first medication this patient should receive

481
00:20:09.120 --> 00:20:11.160
is A, epinephrine; B, diphenhydramine;

482
00:20:11.160 --> 00:20:13.353
C, methylprednisolone; or D, ranitidine?

483
00:20:18.480 --> 00:20:19.470
All right, you all know this.

484
00:20:19.470 --> 00:20:21.060
She's gonna give an EpiPen, epi.

485
00:20:21.060 --> 00:20:22.980
You're gonna give epi, epi, epi right away.

486
00:20:22.980 --> 00:20:26.220
Yes, this patient's got anaphylaxis.

487
00:20:26.220 --> 00:20:28.620
So we see a lot of allergic reactions,

488
00:20:28.620 --> 00:20:32.130
and from anything mild to life threatening, of course.

489
00:20:32.130 --> 00:20:33.600
Urticaria is very common.

490
00:20:33.600 --> 00:20:35.850
Those are the wheals that you'll get.

491
00:20:35.850 --> 00:20:40.850
Angioedema is when the reaction now involves

492
00:20:40.980 --> 00:20:43.773
the deeper dermal layers,

493
00:20:44.978 --> 00:20:47.340
that gives you swelling of the face, neck, and tongue.

494
00:20:47.340 --> 00:20:51.243
Anaphylaxis, alluded too, can happen within seconds.

495
00:20:52.110 --> 00:20:53.820
If it's a bee sting, for example,

496
00:20:53.820 --> 00:20:55.740
the venom gets into your system quickly.

497
00:20:55.740 --> 00:20:57.690
If it's oral, it takes a little bit longer.

498
00:20:57.690 --> 00:20:59.940
Anywhere from a half hour to up to two hours later

499
00:20:59.940 --> 00:21:02.130
you can develop anaphylaxis.

500
00:21:02.130 --> 00:21:04.260
There you get the skin rash, respiratory symptoms,

501
00:21:04.260 --> 00:21:06.240
hypotension, GI distress.

502
00:21:06.240 --> 00:21:08.580
And then there is what we used to call

503
00:21:08.580 --> 00:21:10.890
anaphylactoid reactions.

504
00:21:10.890 --> 00:21:12.900
Understand we don't use that term anymore.

505
00:21:12.900 --> 00:21:16.380
It's called non-immunologic or non-IgE reactions.

506
00:21:16.380 --> 00:21:18.630
And let me explain the difference real quick to you.

507
00:21:18.630 --> 00:21:23.430
So anaphylactic reactions is due to IgE.

508
00:21:23.430 --> 00:21:27.030
Another words, the first time you came in contact

509
00:21:27.030 --> 00:21:32.030
with a peanut or penicillin, you didn't have a problem,

510
00:21:32.190 --> 00:21:35.407
but your body said and your immune system said,

511
00:21:35.407 --> 00:21:37.560
"That looks foreign to me.

512
00:21:37.560 --> 00:21:39.300
I'm gonna make some IgE."

513
00:21:39.300 --> 00:21:44.300
So the next time you take that peanut or penicillin,

514
00:21:44.310 --> 00:21:45.990
I'm gonna have that IgE

515
00:21:45.990 --> 00:21:48.060
attached to all my mast cells, basophils

516
00:21:48.060 --> 00:21:50.310
